'''Radiclib''' is a [[neologism]], an abbreviation of "[[Radicalism|radical]] [[liberal]]". 

== Origin of term ==

The coining of the word is generally attributed to [[Vice_President_of_the_United_States|U.S. Vice President]] [[Spiro Agnew]]. It was used by the [[Richard Nixon|Nixon administration]] to attack the political opposition, implying that the liberals in the [[United States Senate|Senate]] were subversive [http://db.playego.com.br/orafiles/01122005120941567g.swf Example]. Several people on [[Nixon's Enemies List]] were identified as radi-clibs.

== Usage ==

The term surfaced in the [[Watergate scandal]]. According to [[H. R. Haldeman]]'s diary, [[September 12]], [[1970]]:
:"Has several plots he wants hatched. One to infiltrate the [[John William Gardner|John Gardner]] '[[Common Cause]]' deal and needle them and try to push them to left. [...] Next, a front that sounds like [[Students for a Democratic Society|SDS]] to support the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] candidates and praise their liberal records, etc, publicize their 'bad' quotes in guise of praise. Give the senators a 'radiclib' rating."

